f American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): occupational name for someone who dispensed provisions or money, from Middle English <i>spenser(e)</i>, <i>spencer(e)</i> ‘household steward, butler, almoner’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>espenser</i>, Old French <i>despensier</i>). Compare   Spence   and   Spender  . There is some dispute about the origins of the Spencer family, whose most famous member in recent times was the late Princess of Wales, born Lady Diana Spencer (1961–97). Some sources say that they are descended from William the Conqueror's steward, Robert Despencer. What is clear is that by the 15th century they had become prosperous from sheep farming in Northamptonshire. Robert Spencer (died 1627) was said to be the wealthiest man in England. Their titles have included Earls of Sunderland and Earls Spencer; and through the female line the 5th Earl of Sunderland also became Duke of Marlborough in 1733. This connection was the result of the marriage, in 1700, of the 3rd Duke of Sunderland to the daughter of John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough. The youngest son of this union, John Spencer (1708–46), was the father of the 1st Earl Spencer (1734–83)."],"variants":[{"name":"Spence","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a servant employed in the pantry of a great house or monastery, from Middle English <i>spense</i>, <i>spence</i> ‘pantry, larder, storeroom’ (Old French <i>despense</i>, from a Late Latin derivative of <i>dispendere</i>, past participle <i>dispensus</i> ‘to weigh out or dispense’). Compare   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spenser","meanings":["English: variant of   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spender","meanings":["English:","occupational name or status name from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘steward, treasurer’, a shortened form of Middle English, Old French <i>despendour</i>, denoting someone who managed money or supplies. Compare   Spencer  .","alternatively, perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘spender (of money), spendthrift’."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: The Scripture name, in Hebrew, Adham, signifying 'man;' literally earthy, red earth; Rudolph, however, says the name in Ethiopic means ' to be fair, beautiful.' Hence the nurse-name Addy, little Adam."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":25,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":50,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":63,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":72,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":117,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Adam Spencer was born in 1265, in Gloucestershire, England. She married Adam le Despencer about 1278, in Gloucestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"1265–":"1265–Surnud","1261–1349":"1261–1349","1280–1302":"1280–1302","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1382":"1382","1261":"1261","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","circa 1287":"umbes 1287","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1453":"1453","1265":"1265","1287":"1287","circa 1278":"umbes 1278","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"1265–":"1265–Kuollut","1261–1349":"1261–1349","1280–1302":"1280–1302","1287–Male":"1287–Kuollut","1265–Female":"1265–Kuollut","1382":"1382","1261":"1261","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","circa 1287":"noin 1287","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1453":"1453","1265":"1265","1287":"1287","circa 1278":"noin 1278","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"fr":{"1265–":"1265–Décédée","1261–1349":"1261–1349","1280–1302":"1280–1302","1287–Male":"1287–Décédé","1265–Female":"1265–Décédée","1382":"1382","1261":"1261","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","circa 1287":"environ 1287","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1453":"1453","1265":"1265","1287":"1287","circa 1278":"environ 1278","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Adam Spencer est née en 1265, à Gloucestershire, Angleterre. Elle a épousé Adam le Despencer environ 1278, à Gloucestershire, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils et 1 fille."},"de":{"1265–":"1265–Verstorben","1261–1349":"1261–1349","1280–1302":"1280–1302","1287–Male":"1287–Verstorben","1265–Female":"1265–Verstorben","1382":"1382","1261":"1261","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","circa 1287":"um 1287","1337":"1337